<h2>How Features Are Extracted in Real Deployment</h2>
<p><strong>Privacy-Preserving Workflow:</strong> Only numerical features (not video) leave the device.</p>

<div style="background:#e8f4fc; padding:15px; border-radius:8px; margin:20px 0">
  <strong>Step 1: OpenFace 2.0 Feature Extraction</strong><br>
  From interview video, OpenFace extracts these <u>session-level aggregated features</u> per participant:
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Head Pose:</strong> Roll, Pitch, Yaw angles (3D Euler angles) → aggregated as (mean, std, max)</li>
    <li><strong>Eye Gaze:</strong> Normalized (x, y) coordinates → aggregated as (mean, std, max)</li>
    <li><strong>Facial Action Units (FAUs):</strong> Intensities of 17 key muscle movements (e.g., AU04=brow lowerer, AU12=lip corner puller)</li>
    <li><strong>Blink Dynamics:</strong> Frequency and duration per session</li>
  </ul>
  
  <strong>Step 2: Quaternion Encoding (Our Innovation)</strong><br>
  <ul>
    <li>Head pose (roll, pitch, yaw) → converted to 4D quaternion: <code>q = [w, x, y, z]</code></li>
    <li>Preserves 3D rotational structure (avoids gimbal lock at pitch = ±90°)</li>
    <li>Enables QSSA to capture psychomotor retardation patterns</li>
  </ul>
  
  <strong>Step 3: Privacy-Preserving Transmission</strong><br>
  Only the <u>numerical feature vector</u> (not video/audio) is sent to screening server.
</div>

